text: Throughout her tribulations, Bathsheba comes to rely increasingly on her oldest and, as she admits to herself, only real friend, Gabriel. When he gives notice that he is leaving her employ for California, she realises how important he has become to her well-being. That night, she goes alone to visit him in his cottage, to find out why he is deserting her. Pressed, he reluctantly reveals that it is because people have been injuring her good name by gossiping that he wants to marry her. She exclaims that it is "...too absurd ‚Äì too soon ‚Äì to think of, by far!" He bitterly agrees that it is absurd, but when she corrects him, saying that it is only "too soon", he is emboldened to ask once again for her hand in marriage. She accepts, and the two are quietly wed.

text: Watched this last night and was incredibly disappointed. I loved the book, and I love David Nicholls who wrote the screenplay (and his adaptation of Tess of the D'Urburvilles) so I was really let down. The pastoral aspects of the book are translated really well to screen, the casting of the main characters is perfect (Tom Sturridge is better than the Frank Troy I imagined), but the film rattles through the plot far too quickly, and cut out pivotal moments. Martin Sheen is one of our best living actors: so use him! No moments are left to linger long enough, Bathsheba's emotional turmoil over her actions barely considered, and the final chapter of the book insultingly omitted. I'd say if you hadn't read the book you'd have a bit of trouble following. A big let down and I put the blame down to the films editors.

text: Anybody comparing Austen to Hardy or the Brontte sisters does not even understand her novels. They are a satire of first world problems, an entirely new concept at the time. Before, there was just rich and poor people, but in her era, you could be poor like the Bennetts or Fanny Price, or the Baronet¬¥s family in Persuasion, and still enjoy first world privileges. This led to a whole new set of problems that her books describe, and with great class, taste, and in few words. Hardy¬¥s books are gritty, dark, and more for adult reading than for universal enjoyment. It¬¥s like comparing a horror movie to a light thriller. Totally different genres both describing something mysterious, uncertain, and frightening.

text: I enjoyed this film, but it was hampered by its condensed running time; some important plot points were left out and it lacked character development. The 1967 version and the 1998 Masterpiece Theater miniseries were able to explore the story further - for instance, in the 2015 adaptation., Boldwood's obsession with Bathsheba is downplayed; his rivalry with Troy is all but excluded, and Troy's relationship with Fanny barely gets any attention. I also felt that this movie was over-romanticized; however, as I said, still enjoyable.
